    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Creeping, prostrate perennial with a large taproot and elongate, reddish stems that spread out to form mats on sandy areas. Leaves pale and soft, slightly hairy and deeply divided into fine lobes. Large, soft flowers with five bright-yellow petals, cup-shaped, with a green central eye and 10 prominent stamens. Fruit depressed, pentagonal, with a peripheral wing and central knobs.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10085",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Stems typically about 30 cm long. Flowers about 30 mm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10086",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Coastal strip from northern Namaqualand to Cape Peninsula.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10087",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found in sandy areas along the coast, where it can cover large areas with showy patches of bright yellow flowers and can extend almost down to high water mark. Flowers only open in bright sunshine. The large taproot is expanded as a storage organ and is a favoured food of antelope. Also formerly used by hunter-gatherers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10088",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10089",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers August-October.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10090",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>A second, similar species, the Maritzwater or desert primrose <i>G. humifusum</i>, is also found along the West Coast, but also further inland. It has less finely divided leaves and the flowers lack a green eye but become paler towards the centre.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10091",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 430).<br><br>Manning, J (2007). Field Guide to Fynbos. Cape Town: Random House Struik. (p. 340).<br><br>Manning, J & Goldblatt, P (2000). South African Wild Flower Guide 7: West Coast. Botanical Society of South Africa (p. 122).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10092",
